      "content": "Pilots follow a standard pre-flight inspection procedure, which includes checking the pitot tube and its associated components. They visually inspect the pitot tube for any visible obstructions, such as dirt, bugs, or ice. Pilots also use specialized tools like borescopes, which are small, flexible tubes with a camera or light at the end, to inspect hard-to-reach areas inside the pitot tube. Additionally, many aircraft are equipped with pitot heat systems to prevent ice formation. Pilots also rely on their training and experience to recognize any unusual indications from the aircraft's instruments that might suggest a pitot tube blockage. If there's any doubt, they typically avoid flying until the issue is resolved.",
